'''Rebecca Wright''' (5 December 1945, [[Springfield, Ohio]] – 29 January 2006, [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]]) was an [[United States|American]] ballerina, teacher, choreographer and ballet school director.
==Biography== Her background in gymnastics and tap dance was a pivotal influence in early dance training under Josephine Schwarz at the [[Dayton Ballet]]. In 1966 she joined the then prominent but small [[Joffrey Ballet]] as a principal until 1975, becoming a soloist with [[American Ballet Theatre]] (ABT) until her retirement from dance in 1982. She can be seen on television and on [[DVD]] as The Doll in [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]]'s production of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', which was first telecast in 1977.
After her retirement she married fellow dancer [[George de la Peña]] (who also appears in the Baryshnikov ''Nutcracker'') and turned to teaching and choreographing before becoming director of the Washington School of Ballet in 2004.<ref>[http://www.washingtonballet.org/school/index.htm The Washington Ballet.<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
De la Peña and Wright had two children before they separated.
She held a dance professorship at the [[University of California at Los Angeles]] and was director of dance programs at [[Adelphi University]] in [[Garden City, NY]]. She also spent several years as director of dance programs at the private St. Paul's School in Concord, NH.<ref>Adam Bernstein, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/30/AR2006013001636.html "Dancer, Teacher Rebecca Wright; Led Washington School of Ballet"], ''The Washington Post'', January 31, 2006.</ref>
In 2004 she succeeded Mary Day, the legendary founder of the Washington School of Ballet and [[Washington Ballet]], who had run the school for 60 years. Under Wright's leadership school enrollment grew from 350 to 450 students.<ref>[[Sarah Kaufman (critic)|Sarah Kaufman]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/30/AR2006013001629.html "Troubled Washington Ballet Is Further Shaken by Death Of Its School's Director"], ''The Washington Post'', January 31, 2006.</ref>
She died in 2006 at her home in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]], of [[cancer]].
