[[File:Show and tell.jpg|thumb|In this "show and tell" activity, a child is explaining an umbrella they brought in.]] '''Show and tell''' is the practice of showing something to an [[audience]] and telling them about it. In the [[United Kingdom]], [[North America]], [[New Zealand]] and [[Australia]], it is a common classroom activity at early [[elementary school]]. It is used to teach young children the skills of [[public speaking]].<ref name="amer580">Ammer, Christine. (1997). [https://books.google.com/books?id=9re1vfFh04sC&pg=PA580&dq= "show and tell,"] ''The American Heritage dictionary of idioms,'' p. 580.</ref> For example, a child will bring an item from home and will explain to the class why they chose that particular item, where they got it, and other relevant information.
==In popular culture== *The television series ''[[Timothy Goes to School]]'' regularly featured this practice, except that it was referred to as "In the Spotlight," which became the title for one of the program's stories. *In the comic strip ''[[Calvin and Hobbes]]'' by [[Bill Watterson]], show and tell in Calvin's class is an occasionally recurring theme.
