{{Infobox university |name =Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology |image =Toi Ohomai logo.png |motto = |established = May 2016 |faculty =1,036 (2016) |head_label = |head = |students =7,300 [[EFTS]] (2016)<ref>https://en.calameo.com/read/002386530a5863671e2fb</ref> |city = |campus =[[Rotorua]], [[Taupo|Taupō]], [[Tauranga]], [[Tokoroa]], [[Whakatane|Whakatāne]] |country =[[New Zealand]] |affiliations = |website =https://www.toiohomai.ac.nz |address = }}
'''Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology''' is a [[Education in New Zealand#Tertiary education|New Zealand tertiary education institute]] with campuses in [[Rotorua]], [[Tauranga]], and other towns in the [[Bay of Plenty]] region. It was formed in May 2016 after the amalgamation of the Bay of Plenty Polytechnic and [[Waiariki Institute of Technology]]. Toi Ohomai is the largest tertiary provider in the Bay of Plenty, and the third largest institute of technology in New Zealand.<ref name="toi ohomai">{{Cite web|url=https://toiohomai.ac.nz/about-us|title=About Us {{!}} Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology|website=toiohomai.ac.nz|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref>
==History== The ''Waiariki Community College'' was opened in Rotorua in April 1978. Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, the college established additional campuses in Tokoroa, Whakatane, Taupo, [[Turangi]] and [[Kawerau]]. In 1998, the college was renamed ''Waiariki Institute of Technology''. The institute provided education in various areas, such forestry, [[Māori studies]], business management, journalism, sport and music.<ref name="wairiki">{{Cite web|url=https://www.waiariki.ac.nz/about-us/governance-and-management/waiariki-history|title=From Waiariki to Toi Ohomai {{!}} Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology|website=waiariki.ac.nz|access-date=2018-01-28}}</ref>
In 1982, the ''Bay of Plenty Community College'' was opened in Tauranga (later known as ''Bay of Plenty Polytechnic''). The college initially ran various administration, engineering, and agriculture courses, later expanding to other areas such as hospitality, tourism and television. By 1991, the polytechnic had expanded to two main centres - the Windermere Campus in Poike, and the Bongard Centre in downtown Tauranga. In 2010, a total of 9,443 students were studying at Bay of Plenty Polytechnic.<ref name="bop poly">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boppoly.ac.nz/go/history|title=History {{!}} Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology|website=boppoly.ac.nz|access-date=2018-01-28}}</ref>
On 1 May 2016, the two institutions merged to form Toi Ohomai Institute of Technology. The new name was gifted by local iwi, and means "to aim high and achieve great heights; to be awakened by learning."<ref name="toi ohomai" />
